sec.p:
The Panel notes that the P95 estimated intake of vitamin B6 from food consumption only (i.e. without food supplements) is up to 1.2 mg/day in infants (4 to < 12 months), up to 1.9 mg/day in toddlers (1 to < 3 years), up to 2.7 mg/day in other children (3 to < 10 years), up to 4 mg/day in adolescents (10 to < 18 years) and up to 5 mg/day in adults (≥ 18 years), across surveys included in EFSA's intake assessment (EFSA NDA Panel, 2016) (Table 
3

). Intakes are slightly lower in females, except for female toddlers, mainly due to smaller quantities of food consumed per day. National reports of more recent data do not indicate that vitamin B6 intakes of high (P95) consumers in EU Member States may exceed EFSA estimates of intake from food sources only, but comparisons are difficult owing to the different methodologies and food composition tables used.

